            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>To the shades of the underworld. Mevia Faustin[---], lived for 21(?) years.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#AA">
                <p>Despite the lacuna on the right, it is likely that the epitaph is for a woman, Mevia Faustina. The gens Mevia is well-attested in Thermae Himeraeae, see <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000119">ISic000119</ref> and elsewhere in Sicily, notably at Tauromenium <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000282">ISic000282</ref>, Halaesa <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000767">ISic000767</ref> and Lilybaeum <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000625">ISic000625</ref>. Cicero also attests to Maeviae in Sicily, notably a Maevius, the scribe of Verres, who is named at Cic. Verr. 2.3.175). There is a Greek version of the name (Μηβία) also attested at Thermae Himeraeae, <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001168">ISic001168</ref>.</p>
            </div>
